03952nam a22005655i 9780300168372DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20102010ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001683727 a10.12987/97803001683722doi  a(DE-B1597)486204  a(OCoLC)1046611317  a(OCoLC)1046994720  a(OCoLC)1049683208  a(OCoLC)1054875985  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aML3845b.R69 2010eb 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a781/.112221 aRosen, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMusic and Sentiment /cCharles Rosen. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (160 p.) :bMusic examples throughout  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPrologue -- tI Fixing the Meaning of Complex Signs -- tII Pre-Classical Sentiment -- tIII Contradictory Sentiments -- tIV The C Minor Style -- tV Beethoven's Expansion -- tVI Romantic Intensity -- tVII Obsessions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow does a work of music stir the senses, creating feelings of joy, sadness, elation, or nostalgia? Though sentiment and emotion play a vital role in the composition, performance, and appreciation of music, rarely have these elements been fully observed. In this succinct and penetrating book, Charles Rosen draws upon more than a half century as a performer and critic to reveal how composers from Bach to Berg have used sound to represent and communicate emotion in mystifyingly beautiful ways.Through a range of musical examples, Rosen details the array of stylistic devices and techniques used to represent or convey sentiment. This is not, however, a listener's guide to any "correct" response to a particular piece. Instead, Rosen provides the tools and terms with which to appreciate this central aspect of musical aesthetics, and indeed explores the phenomenon of contradictory sentiments embodied in a single motif or melody. Taking examples from Chopin, Schumann, Wagner, and Liszt, he traces the use of radically changing intensities in the Romantic works of the nineteenth century and devotes an entire chapter to the key of C minor. He identifies a "unity of sentiment" in Baroque music and goes on to contrast it with the "obsessive sentiments" of later composers including Puccini, Strauss, and Stravinsky. A profound and moving work, Music and Sentiment is an invitation to a greater appreciation of the crafts of composition and performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300168372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300168372.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles